// Maintenance window task registration
//
// Examine a task that the maintenance window runs against its registered targets — the document or
// function `taskArn` points to, the IAM `iamRole()` SSM assumes to execute it, the priority within
// the window, and the parallelism guardrails (`maxConcurrency`, `maxErrors`, `cutoffBehavior`).
// `taskType` is one of `RUN_COMMAND`, `AUTOMATION`, `LAMBDA`, or `STEP_FUNCTIONS`. Selected by the
// composite `region/windowId/windowTaskId` key returned by `DescribeMaintenanceWindowTasks`.
private aws.ssm.maintenanceWindow.task @defaults("name taskType priority") {
  // Maintenance window ID the task is registered to
  windowId string
  // Task ID within the maintenance window
  windowTaskId string
  // Region where the task is registered
  region string
  // Task name
  name string
  // Description of the task
  description string
  // Task type
  //
  // One of `RUN_COMMAND`, `AUTOMATION`, `LAMBDA`, or `STEP_FUNCTIONS`.
  taskType string
  // Resource the task uses during execution
  //
  // For `RUN_COMMAND` and `AUTOMATION`, the SSM document name or ARN; for `LAMBDA`, the function
  // name or ARN; for `STEP_FUNCTIONS`, the state machine ARN.
  taskArn string
  // ARN of the IAM service role SSM assumes when running the task
  serviceRoleArn string
  // IAM service role SSM assumes when running the task
  iamRole() aws.iam.role
  // Priority of the task within the window (lower number = higher priority)
  priority int
  // Maximum number of targets the task runs against in parallel
  maxConcurrency string
  // Maximum number of errors allowed before the task stops being scheduled
  maxErrors string
  // Cutoff behavior for tasks still running when the window closes
  //
  // One of `CONTINUE_TASK` or `CANCEL_TASK`.
  cutoffBehavior string
  // Targets the task runs against (key/values pairs from the registration)
  targets []dict
}

